subSection.paragraph:
Tribe Litini in the subfamily Gelechiinae is delimited by frequently reduced gnathos of the male genitalia; absence of culcitula; presence of glandiductors and often fused juxta with vinculum and sacculus (for more details see: Bidzilya & Mey 2011;
Ponomarenko et al . 2021a
). Additional characteristic features of the tribe are: strongly developed and usually modified male abdominal segment VIII; long apophyses anteriores; normally rhomboid signum with serrated edges in female genitalia (Piskunov 1973) and forewing usually with tufts of raised scales (Huemer & Karsholt 1999; Lee & Brown 2008 ). Tribe Litini comprises about 40 genera worldwide ( Janse 1958 ; Huemer & Karsholt 1999; Ponomarenko 2005 ; Lee & Brown 2008 , 2013 ; Cepeda 2018 ; Omelko & Omelko 2020 ;
Ponomarenko et al . 2021a
, b). Litini is representing in Afrotropic by 14 genera including about 40 species ( Janse 1958 ; Bidzilya & Mey 2011).

subSubSection.paragraph:
Female genitalia with papillae anales subtriangular, covered with short setae; apophyses posteriores 1.5– 2.5 times longer than the length of apophyses posteriores; segment VIII broad, unmodified, weakly sclerotized; apophyses anteriores straight, usually inflated at apex; ductus bursae either slender (
P. sagittata
) to moderately broad (
P. minima
sp. nov.
,
